Main finding: the evidence does **not** support the broad claim that AI coding agents generally make experienced developers measurably faster on real work in familiar codebases. Gains are supported for narrower cases: well-specified, implementation-heavy, often greenfield or junior/recent-hire work. The strict target setting is contradicted by METR’s experienced-developer RCT, with the important caveat that METR’s later update says current 2026 effects are likely different but not cleanly measured.

Most important divergence: self-reported speedup and measured speed can sharply disagree. METR found developers believed AI sped them up while measured task time slowed; NAV found perceived productivity had negligible correlation with commit metrics.

